background

parameter defines which hypothesis is supposed to be tested from this set.

h1

  • category: scene category (man-made vs natural)
  • h1_N1: mean amplitude (call with: h1_N1)

h2

  • novelty: image novelty (new vs old)
  • h2_amp: fronto-central mean amplitude (call with: h2_amp)
  • h2_theta: fronto-central theta (call with: h2_theta)
  • h2_alpha: posterior alpha (call with: h2_alpha)

h3

  • recognition: successful recognition (hit vs miss)
  • h3_amp: mean amplitude any channel any time (call with: h3_amp)
  • h3_spectral: spectral any freq, channel, and time (call with: h3_spectral)

h4

  • memory: subsequent memory (remembered vs forgotten)
  • h4_amp: mean amplitude any channel any time (call with: h4_amp)
  • h4_spectral: spectral any freq, channel, and time (call with: h4_spectral)
now_h <- params$now_h
now_stage <- params$now_stage 
now_num <- NA     # order of hypothesis in instruction document (helps in output file)
now_text <- NA    # info about hypothesis
now_cond <- NA    # predictor variable (always has 2 levels)
now_levels <- NA  # name of levels of predictor variable

# effect coding
# =============
# - if you use [-1, +1], the estimates change (but not p values).
# This is because the predictors are scaled differently.
# - this centers the predictors
# - the second level becomes the baseline in the model
now_contrasts <- c(0.5, -0.5) 
now_EEG <- NA     # outcome variable
now_exclude_bad <- "N"  # Y/N: exclude trials labeled as bad during preprocessing

# (To avoid biases of initial (MNE) EEG figures, we eyeballed the data and
# screened for extreme values. However, these are included here because below,
# outliers are detected across all trials and robust methods are used. The
# criterion defines the number of SD around each condition mean that are not
# considered outliers.)
now_outcut <- 3 # eg 3 means values have to be more than 3 SDs from the condition mean

now_ROPE <- c(-.1, .1)    # region of practical equivalence

# default prior:
# normal distribution with m = 0 and sd = 2
now_prior <- brms::prior_string("normal(0,2)", class = "b")

# stage 2 may use prior from stage 1; default is no
now_s2_use_s1_prior <- "N" # Y/N to tell stage 2 to use the prior from stage 1

# scaling factor for the posterior sd in stage 2
# taking the sd from the posterior in stage 1 as the prior in stage 2 may be too optimistic
# multiply the obtained sd of posterior by the scaling factor
now_scaling <- 3 # default in bayestestR
# h1: category
if (now_h == "h1_N1"){
  now_num <- 1
  now_text <- ("There is an effect of scene category (i.e., a difference between images\nshowing man-made vs. natural environments) on the amplitude of the\nN1 component, i.e. the first major negative EEG voltage deflection.")
  now_cond <- "category"
  now_levels <- c("man-made", "natural")
  now_EEG  <- "h1_N1"

# h2: novelty
} else if (now_h == "h2_amp"){
  now_num <- 2
  now_text <- ("There are effects of image novelty (i.e., between images shown for the first\ntime/new vs. repeated/old images) within the time-range from 300–500 ms on\nEEG voltage at fronto-central channels.")
  now_cond <- "novelty"
  now_levels <- c("new", "old")
  now_EEG  <- "h2_amp"

} else if (now_h == "h2_theta"){
  now_num <- 3
  now_text <- ("There are effects of image novelty (i.e., between images shown for the first\ntime/new vs. repeated/old images) within the time-range from 300–500 ms on\ntheta power at fronto-central channels.")
  now_cond <- "novelty"
  now_levels <- c("new", "old")
  now_EEG  <- "h2_theta"

} else if (now_h == "h2_alpha"){
  now_num <- 4
  now_text <- ("There are effects of image novelty (i.e., between images shown for the first\ntime/new vs. repeated/old images) within the time-range from 300–500 ms on\nalpha power at posterior channels.")
  now_cond <- "novelty"
  now_levels <- c("new", "old")
  now_EEG  <- "h2_alpha"

# h3: recognition
} else if (now_h == "h3_amp"){
  now_num <- 5
  now_text <- ("There are effects of successful recognition of old images (i.e., a difference\nbetween old images correctly recognized as old [hits] vs. old images\nincorrectly judged as new [misses]) on\nEEG voltage at any channels, at any time.")
  now_cond <- "recognition"
  now_levels <- c("hit", "miss")
  now_EEG  <- "h3_amp"

} else if (now_h == "h3_spectral"){
  now_num <- 6
  now_text <- ("There are effects of successful recognition of old images (i.e., a difference\nbetween old images correctly recognized as old [hits] vs. old images\nincorrectly judged as new [misses]) on\nEEG voltage at any channels, at any time.")
  now_cond <- "recognition"
  now_levels <- c("hit", "miss")
  now_EEG  <- "h3_spectral"

# h4: memory
} else if (now_h == "h4_amp"){
  now_num <- 7
  now_text <- ("There are effects of subsequent memory (i.e., a difference between images that\nwill be successfully remembered vs. forgotten on a subsequent repetition) on\nEEG voltage at any channels, at any time.")
  now_cond <- "memory"
  now_levels <- c("remembered", "forgotten")
  now_EEG  <- "h4_amp"

} else if (now_h == "h4_spectral"){
  now_num <- 8
  now_text <- ("There are effects of subsequent memory (i.e., a difference between images that\nwill be successfully remembered vs. forgotten on a subsequent repetition) on\nspectral power, at any frequencies, at any channels, at any time.")
  now_cond <- "memory"
  now_levels <- c("remembered", "forgotten")
  now_EEG  <- "h4_spectral"
}

# if stage 2 is supposed to use prior from stage 1, read it from file
if ((now_s2_use_s1_prior == "Y") && now_stage == 2){
  # check for prior from stage 1
  stopifnot("No file with priors is available" =
            file.exists("results/prior_posterior.txt"))
  # read in prior
  df_distr <- read_delim("results/prior_posterior.txt", delim = "\t",
                          show_col_types = FALSE)
  # find row for hypothesis and stage 1
  df_distr$check <- (df_distr$Hypothesis == now_h) &
                    (df_distr$Stage == 1)

  # keep this row
  df_distr <- df_distr %>% 
    filter(df_distr$check) %>% 
    select(-check)

  stopifnot("No prior saved from stage 1" = nrow(df_distr) > 0)
  stopifnot("Too many priors saved from stage 1" = nrow(df_distr) == 1)
  
  # redefine prior
  now_prior <- prior_string(paste0("normal(", 
                      round(df_distr$Posterior_m, 2), ", ", 
                      # maybe rescale posterior to make it wider
                      round(df_distr$Posterior_sd * now_scaling, 2), ")"), class = "b")
}

Stefan, A., Lengersdorff, L., & Wagenmakers, E.-J. (2022). A two-stage Bayesian sequential assessment of exploratory hypotheses [Preprint]. PsyArXiv. https://doi.org/10.31234/osf.io/qwuyf

read data

input:

  • fp = subject id
  • trial = trial
  • cond = condition codes (e.g., man-made/new/correct rejection/forgotten)
  • bad (1 or 0) = 1: artifact rejection in MNE labeled as bad
  • lots of outcome variables
df <- read_tsv(file = "data/data.tsv", show_col_types = FALSE) %>% 
  rowwise() %>%          
  mutate(condlist = str_split(cond, "/"),
        category = condlist[1],
        novelty = condlist[2],
        recognition = condlist[3],
        memory = condlist[4]) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(na_if(across(category:memory),"NA")) %>% 
  select(-condlist)

if (now_exclude_bad == "Y") {
  df <- df %>% 
    filter(bad == 0)
}

# select sample
# stage1 shows whether subject was randomly selected to be in the subsample (ie Stage 1):
#   1 = subject is in Stage 1
#   0 = subject is not in Stage 1
if (now_stage == 1){
  # stage1 (keep small subset of subjects)
  df <- df %>% 
        filter(stage1 == 1)
} else if (now_stage == 2){
  # stage2 (keep remaining subjects)
  df <- df %>% 
        filter(stage1 == 0)
} else {
  # use all subjects
  stopifnot("Stage must be between 1 and 3!" = now_stage == 3)
}

# keep relevant columns
df <- df %>% 
  select(id, trial, cond, bad, all_of(now_cond), all_of(now_EEG))  
  # why all_of? see https://tidyselect.r-lib.org/reference/faq-external-vector.html

# define comparison as factor
df[[now_cond]] <- factor(df[[now_cond]], levels = now_levels)
contrasts(df[[now_cond]]) <- now_contrasts

# add copy of relevant variables
# easier for plotting
df$now_compare <- df[[now_cond]]
df$EEG <- df[[now_EEG]]

# keep only relevant trials
df <- df %>% 
  filter(!is.na(now_compare))

outliers

criterion was defined initially as 3 x SD

zscore is computed for each EEG value in reference to its own condition mean. The criterion refers to numbers of SDs around its own condition mean that are not considered outliers

shapiro.test(sample(df$EEG, 
             # 5000 is max for Shapiro test
             5000, replace = FALSE))
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  sample(df$EEG, 5000, replace = FALSE)
## W = 0.99241, p-value = 1.065e-15
# for transformation advice, see here
# https://r-coder.com/box-cox-transformation-r/

# make positive
x <- df$EEG - min(df$EEG) + .01
cat("For some of the spectral analyses, the data do not look normally distributed but skewed.\nFor completeness, conduct a boxcox transformation for the frequency data.\nStart by computing lambda.")
MASS::boxcox(lm(x ~ 1, y = TRUE))
bc <- MASS::boxcox(lm(x ~ 1, y = TRUE))
lambda <- bc$x[which.max(bc$y)]
df$EEGlambda <-  (x ^ lambda - 1) / lambda
cat("The figure suggests some deviation from a normal distribution.\nA Boxcox transformation was computed (after shifting the values to positive).\nThe best lambda was ", round(lambda,2), ".\n\nIf lambda is close to 1, the transformation does not change the data much; thus, it is recommended to leave the data as they are.\n\nNonetheless, the data were transformed: \n(1) shifting to positive\n(2) adjusting with exact lambda\n\n", sep ="")

qqnorm(df$EEGlambda, main = "Normal Q-Q Plot after Lambda transformation")
qqline(df$EEGlambda, col = "blue", lwd = 2, lty = 2)

Shapiro_trans <- shapiro.test(sample(df$EEGlambda,
                                 # 5000 is max for Shapiro test
                                 5000, replace = FALSE))
Shapiro_trans$data.name <- "EEG after lambda transformation across conditions"

print(Shapiro_trans)
cat("Because the transformation did not seem to help much, the untransformed data were used in the final analyses.")
df$EEGlambda <- NULL
rm(x)

memory means

means and 95%CI (from standard t tests)

df_means <- df %>% 
  group_by(now_compare, id) %>% 
  summarise(amps = mean(EEG), .groups = "drop") %>%
  group_by(now_compare) %>%
  summarise(N = n(),
            Mean = mean(amps),
            CI95_LL = t.test(amps)$conf.int[1],
            CI95_UL = t.test(amps)$conf.int[2],
           .groups = "drop")
df_means[[str_to_title(now_cond)]] <- df_means$now_compare
df_means <- df_means %>%

model formula

model_formula <- formula(paste0(now_EEG, " ~ 1 + ", now_cond, 
                         " + (1 + ", now_cond, " | id)"))

model formula: h4_amp ~ 1 + memory + (1 + memory | id)

fit model

Bayesian robust LMM

set.seed(nowseed)
# fit a linear mixed-effects model to data
data <- df
model_name <- paste0(now_h, "_stage", now_stage, "_brm_robust")
assign(get("model_name"), brms::brm(model_formula,
                           data = data,
                           family = student(),
                           inits = 0,
                           prior = now_prior,
                           file = sprintf("results/models/model_%s.RDS", model_name),
                           iter = my_iter, 
                           warmup = my_warm, 
                           seed = nowseed,
                           control = list(adapt_delta = 0.99),
                           # needed for model comparison
                           save_pars = save_pars(all = TRUE),
                           sample_prior = "yes"))
mod_h <- get(model_name)

model name: h4_amp_stage3_brm_robust

# str(posterior_mod)

coeffsall <- coeffsall %>% 
  mutate(coeff = rowMeans(matrix(posterior_mod, 
                                 nrow=dim(posterior_mod)[3], byrow = TRUE)),
         now_compare = grepl(paste0("b_", now_cond, "1"), value), 
         now_compare_id = grepl(paste0("r_id\\[\\d+,", now_cond, "1\\]"), value))
idcodes <- unique(mod_h$data$id)

# comparison coeff
compcoef <- coeffsall$coeff[coeffsall$now_compare]

REid <- coeffsall %>% 
  filter(now_compare_id) %>% 
  mutate(id = idcodes,

  kable_styling()
Parameter Prior_Distribution Prior_Location Prior_Scale Prior_df
b_memory1 normal 0 2 NA 
prior_distr <- prior_cond$Prior_Distribution
prior_m <- prior_cond$Prior_Location
prior_sd <- prior_cond$Prior_Scale
stopifnot("Prior is not a normal distribution" = prior_distr == "normal")
prior_cond <- distribution_normal(4000, mean = prior_m, sd = prior_sd, random = FALSE)

posterior

posterior may be used as prior in next stage (as described by Stefan et al., 2022)

data: obtained posterior distribution

normal: median and SD from the data distribution are used to define a normal distribution (m = median, SD = SD).

normal_scaled: median and SD x 3 (i.e., SD = 3 x SD) from the data distribution are used to define a normal distribution.

goal is to show that the normal distribution fits the data well enough. Note that it is the m and SD that are saved. If these are used as the prior for a later analysis, the SD may be multiplied by a scaling factor (to avoid overfitting). Therefore, the figure also shows the normal with a scaling factor of 3 (i.e., SD = 3 x SD).

post_distr <- distribution_normal(4000, mean = post_m, sd = post_sd, random = FALSE)
post_distr3 <- distribution_normal(4000, mean = post_m, 
                                   sd = post_sd * now_scaling, random = FALSE)
bfdata <- tibble(data = posteriors[[paste0("b_", now_cond, "1")]], 
                 normal = post_distr, 
                 normal_scaled = post_distr3) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = everything(), 
               names_to = "Distribution",
               values_to = "effect")
ggplot(bfdata) +
  geom_density(aes(x = effect, color = Distribution), size = 1.5) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = post_m), linetype = "solid", 
             color = "blue", size = 1) +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = post_m - post_sd), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = post_m + post_sd), linetype = "dashed") +
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 0), color = "black", linetype = "solid", size = 1) +
  labs(title = paste0("Posterior distributions for effect (Median +/- SD)"))
